# CaptionDB Docker Engineering Contract

## Purpose

This contract defines the Docker, containerization, and deployment standards for CaptionDB.

Docker is the official deployment mechanism for:

- Local Development
- AMD Developer Hackathon Submission
- Production Deployment
- Continuous Integration

Every container must be reproducible, secure, portable, and optimized.

---

# Engineering Philosophy

Docker containers are production artifacts.

Never treat Docker as an afterthought.

Every Dockerfile should be:

- Reproducible
- Minimal
- Secure
- Fast
- Maintainable
- Deterministic

---

# Container Strategy

Separate containers by responsibility.

Examples:

Frontend

Backend

Future Database

Future Redis

Future Monitoring

Never combine unrelated services into one image.

---

# Multi-Stage Builds

Always use multi-stage builds.

Separate:

Builder

↓

Runtime

Never ship development tooling inside production images.

---

# Base Images

Prefer official images.

Pin image versions.

Never use:

latest

Example:

python:3.12-slim

instead of

python:latest

---

# Image Size

Minimize image size.

Remove:

Temporary files

Package caches

Unused build tools

Unused libraries

Keep production images lean.

---

# User Permissions

Containers must never run as root.

Create dedicated application users.

Assign minimum required permissions.

---

# Working Directory

Use explicit working directories.

Example:

/app

Avoid relying on default directories.

---

# Dependency Installation

Install only required dependencies.

Separate:

Development

Production

Testing

Avoid unnecessary packages.

---

# Layer Optimization

Maximize Docker layer caching.

Order instructions:

Base image

↓

Dependencies

↓

Configuration

↓

Application source

↓

Startup

Avoid invalidating cache unnecessarily.

---

# Environment Variables

Never hardcode:

API Keys

Secrets

Passwords

Tokens

Model IDs

URLs

Configuration values

Everything must come from environment variables or mounted configuration.

---

# Configuration

Mount configuration when appropriate.

Support:

Development

Testing

Production

Do not maintain separate Dockerfiles for every environment unless justified.

---

# Volumes

Use volumes only when necessary.

Examples:

Uploads

Logs

Cache

Future persistent storage

Avoid writing application state inside the container filesystem.

---

# Networking

Expose only required ports.

Avoid unnecessary services.

Use named Docker networks.

Support future service isolation.

---

# Health Checks

Every production container must define a health check.

Health checks should verify:

Application availability

Required dependencies

Configuration readiness

Avoid expensive health checks.

---

# Startup

Startup should:

Validate configuration

Initialize logging

Verify required services

Fail fast if critical dependencies are unavailable.

---

# Shutdown

Support graceful shutdown.

Close:

Connections

Workers

Threads

File handles

Avoid corrupted state.

---

# Logging

Write logs to stdout/stderr.

Avoid writing logs inside the container filesystem.

Container platforms should collect logs.

---

# Build Context

Keep Docker build context minimal.

Exclude:

.git

tests

documentation

cache

temporary files

node_modules

Python cache

Use .dockerignore.

---

# Docker Ignore

Maintain a complete .dockerignore.

Exclude unnecessary files to reduce build size and improve performance.

---

# Secrets

Never copy secrets into Docker images.

Never bake credentials into layers.

Use runtime environment variables.

---

# Python Optimization

Use:

PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1

PYTHONUNBUFFERED=1

Optimize dependency installation.

---

# Frontend Builds

Frontend should build separately.

Only production assets belong in production images.

Development tooling must not ship.

---

# Backend Builds

Backend should install only runtime dependencies.

Development packages belong in development images only.

---

# Docker Compose

Compose files should support:

Development

Production

Future testing

Separate concerns clearly.

---

# Restart Policy

Define restart policies where appropriate.

Avoid infinite restart loops during development.

---

# Resource Limits

Support configurable:

CPU

Memory

Workers

Timeouts

Future GPU allocation

Do not hardcode resource assumptions.

---

# AMD GPU Compatibility

Design containers to support AMD GPU environments.

Avoid assumptions tied to CUDA.

Keep GPU-specific configuration abstracted.

Support future ROCm-compatible deployments where applicable.

---

# Fireworks Compatibility

Fireworks credentials should be injected at runtime.

Never bake provider configuration into the image.

---

# Security

Run as non-root.

Use minimal privileges.

Avoid privileged containers.

Avoid unnecessary Linux capabilities.

Keep attack surface minimal.

---

# Image Reproducibility

Pinned dependency versions.

Pinned base images.

Deterministic builds.

Avoid downloading unpredictable resources during startup.

---

# CI/CD Compatibility

Docker builds should execute successfully inside GitHub Actions.

Avoid interactive build steps.

Support automated testing.

---

# Performance

Optimize:

Image size

Startup time

Layer cache

Dependency installation

Cold start

Memory footprint

---

# Testing

Every Docker image should support:

Build verification

Startup verification

Health check verification

Smoke testing

---

# Documentation

Document:

Build commands

Run commands

Environment variables

Volume mounts

Ports

Health checks

Known limitations

---

# Docker Review Checklist

Before completing implementation verify:

✓ Multi-stage build

✓ Minimal image

✓ Non-root user

✓ Pinned versions

✓ No hardcoded secrets

✓ Health check implemented

✓ Environment variables configured

✓ .dockerignore updated

✓ Layer caching optimized

✓ Logs written to stdout/stderr

✓ Startup validated

✓ Graceful shutdown supported

✓ AMD-compatible design

✓ Fireworks configuration externalized

✓ Documentation updated

If any item fails, revise the implementation before completion.

---

End of Docker Engineering Contract.
